(166, 2, 1, 'To Thee the cause of every sigh is known,'),
(166, 2, 2, 'Thou who dost feel the sorrows of Thine own;'),
(166, 2, 3, 'Unspoken fears, and questions hard to solve,'),
(166, 2, 4, 'Before the rays of heav\'nly light dissolve.'),
(166, 3, 1, 'Thy well-proved love our confidence inspires'),
(166, 3, 2, 'To count upon the grace that never tires;'),
(166, 3, 3, 'So would we make Thine interests, Lord, our care,'),
